albert al camarillo the clayman institute for gender research skip to main content standford university the clayman institute for gender research the clayman institute for gender research home programs news strategic focus events about research fellowships library media center gender news no news found events no events found you are here home people albert al camarillo albert al camarillo leon sloss jr memorial professor school of humanities & sciences professor of history school of humanities & sciences al camarillo was born and raised in the south central los angeles community of compton he entered the university of california at los angeles as a freshman in 1966 and continued his education at ucla in the ph d program in us history where he received his doctorate in 1975 and where his dissertation was nominated that year as one of the best ph d theses in the nation in american history camarillo was appointed to the faculty in the department of history at stanford university in 1975 a position he still holds he is widely regarded as one of the founding scholars of the field of mexican american history and chicano studies and has recieved numerous awards the most recent being the miriam roland prize for volunteer service for 2005 further information about al camarillo is available from his website donate make a donation social links facebook twitter youtube scribd contact serra house 589 capistrano way stanford ca 94305 8640 map 650 723 1994 gender email stanford edu
